author: P
text: I stopped listening to contemporary radio around 1995 partly because I was dissatisfied with then-modern music, which seemed to have been in a state of degeneration since the early 90s. Finally, when I first saw this music video, I was entranced by the masks worn by the members of Arcade Fire. I played it as a joke for my girlfriend, unleashing an unintended consequence: I ended up LOVING every second of the song!

author: Junkai Yang
text: I can't always get the hate from people towards this whole album. This album is the definition of what one of the best bands in world should do - pioneering, experimenting and innovating! The infusion of 70s,80s disco, electronica, dance punk (yah! when you know James Murphy was on the main producers list), twisted synthesizing and also the core of Arcade Fire themselves together with their long-standing interpretations of aesthetics, life and death. This was one of their best works, in fact, all 4 LPs were equally brilliant to me.

author: heatbug
text: I'm sure there are plenty of write ups on theories about what this video is about. The symbolism is a little obtuse but at least part of it seems to imply the song is about a couple that was once in love. They slowly grew apart, and as a last ditch effort to revitalize their relationship they start having children. The coffin full of baby dolls is the give away along with the truck. The coffin is bright and reflective, covered partly by CD's in places. I think this is the death of the couple's partying lifestyle. The babies inside are the consequences of leaving their old life behind. The truck saying NINE in bold lettering on the back, the split down the middle being vaginal in nature, and then the people in the back throwing babies out is multiple births. The couple just keep having kids to fill their loveless void.

text: And that last night there at those courts before leaving, all they told me was be very careful driving that truck and generator out of those gates. they were 200 years old they told me. author: ramirobot
text: About Bowie participation, from Wikipedia:\n\n Richard Reed Parry noted, "It was just after The Next Day had come out. He basically just came by the studio in New York while we were mixing, just to have a listen to the stuff we were doing. He offered to lend us his services because he really liked the song. In fact, he basically threatened us ‚Äì he was like, 'If you don't hurry up and mix this song, I might just steal it from you!' So we thought, well why don't we go one better, why don't you sing on our version? Thankfully he obliged, and we were really happy about that."

author: stashray
text: another example of an album that becomes personified. Ziggy Stardust. That album turns into a person. Or maybe after listening to it, it was just me, who turned into someone. i'm 9 or 10 years old and i can singalong to all the songs. Now i'm 48  and i can still singalong to them and it would come as no surprise as to why Arcade Fire since 2007 has had such an affect on me. i'd heard on the radio where.no.cars.go and liked it but it wasn't until a certain day with certain things milling over in my head that i heard that song that  i cannot listen to today, Intervention. I was in Rushcutters Bay Sydney driving and i had to pull over and remained still and listened. near its end, the crescendo builds to 'been working for the church while YOUR LIFE FALLS APART" and i just lost it. "this is me, this was just now and still is" and i freaked out. i drove to the nearest cd store and bought it. Then funeral after and always i grow or expand after each album. things clear up for me,  and other things return to be addressed and new thoughts come to life to pursue. Yep, The ArcadeFire Brigade. They don't put fires out, they start 'em!

author: stashray
text: DB has been making himself at home in my head since i was 9, 10 or 11. And so yeah, learning of his death, certainly felt like something. Like i said, like a family friend, a person you grew up with inside your house and he made you know about mad love and soul love and the one who kneels before the grave of a brave son who gave his life to save a slogan that hovers between the headstones and her eyes. And all i have is my love of love and love is not loving. and then imagining your pushing through a market square where so many mothers were sighing because news had just come over...we had five years left to die in. And my brain felt like a warehouse it had no room left to spare i hafd to cram so many things in trhere and all the fat skinny people and all the tall short people and all the no.body people....And i never thought that i would NEED so many people

author: stashray
text: sorry for the David Bowie reflection in the middle of a song called Reflecktor from an album called Reflecktor by a band called Arcade Fire whom David Bowie was a great supporter of and a close valued friend who happens to sing in this very song called Reflecktor with Arcade Fire and the line he sings is sung in an elevated fashion, its highnote like he is making a point... thought you were praying to the resurrector....to which Win sings back, but he's not singing it back to DB, he's singing it back to us without emotion, just making a statement....(oh guess what folks)....turns out it was just a reflecktor. Then DB sings it again but a little more higher this time sounds more pressing....thought you were praying to the resurrector, Win!? What happened? and then Win breaks, and concedes and shows some emotion, he sounds a little bummed out by discovering that the resurrector was not ever once real..... it was just a reflector.... all along.\n\n¬†in that little exchange between DB and Win it feels like DB is pressuring Win  to confess to a mistake or something... It's like DB was trying to punk him out. You know, like, Ha ha i thought you were praying to the resurrector, what happened? what're you doing now because you're  not praying to him are you? because why, Win? and Win has to tell us all why there is no such thing as the resurrector, and it's because it's always been the doings of the Reflecktor

author: stashray
text: The day i found out he died, i remember later in the day feeling like someone close, a family friend had passed away. My two older sisters loved his music, they were big fans. At any given day the house stereo was blaring out any one of the many bowie albums. I probably wasn't even in my teens before i pretty much knew every bowie song there was. And whenever you sang one you'd do it in front of mirror. He'd have been like an imaginary friend to me. Hence that feeling i had the day he died. He was like a member of the house i grew up in. and there was only one record player in the house and when it was on you'd hear from anywhere, in any room and even outside. I was prob 11 or 12 and knew all his songs.\n\nI've never reflected on that, like that, before.

author: stashray
text: Eleven years old and singing along all these mad love songs. and they were mad.love.songs too and you had to mimic him too and get the feeling into the voice too Need i say more than Heroes. thats a madlove song and he screams the whole song long. That 11 year old is taking on some heavy weight. ...we can beat them forever and ever...i.will.be.king...said the 11 year old and you, he screamed.... you.will.be.queen. and whoknows maybe a will was willed at that time for that 11 year old boy, a first generation australian who is only there and not in Lithuania because of War.

text: "We fell in love when we were nineteen, and now we're staring at a screen.." \nThat goes for a lot of people around me.  People change a lot between late-teens and mid-twenties, but yeay they got so comfortable in their relationships that now they're afraid to be alone. Even though their partners likes completely different things than they do.

author: Peter Timowreef
text: @Cynthia Elkhouly\nOk Cynthia, please accept my apologies for saying such a blatantly ignorant thing.

author: Elra Beechum
text: +Peter Timowreef  I hear you man, it's definitely "and now we're staring at a screen", which is a lyric that definitely has a lot of resonance with me and people I know. I think the relationship in the song has faded into a detached and depressing reflection of itself, and it's the same kind of relationship that you mention. Really sad.

author: Peter Timowreef
text: @Tom Lute\nYea bloody screens man. Entertainment so readily available we stop looking for it. And when you stop looking you miss all of the marvelous oppurtunities in crazy directions that might've presented themselves if we'd just go out there.\nBut no, we don't have to go to that museum, orchestra, park, party, friends house, show, circus, bar, pub, theater, cinema, restaurant or bowling-alley because we got mother truckin screens. I'm doing it right now ffs.

author: Elra Beechum
text: +Peter Timowreef Haha exactly, this entire album is essentially directed at the kind of people who sit around commenting on youtube videos haha. And here we are! Even though I'm screen-hopping at this very moment, I feel happy that my best memories of this song are of dancing with other people to it, or playing it in cars with people on our way to somewhere awesome. No screens involved! Gives me hope, at least for myself.

author: Andrew Allen
text: I was really excited when this whole album came out and it sounds cool, but it just doesn't have the same substance/nostalgia/beauty/comfort/poetry that Funeral, Neon Bible and the Suburbs possess. I listened to Neon Bible and the Suburbs so many times in the car front to back. Those albums take you to a different place no matter how you are feeling and Reflektor feels like an after party you weren't invited too. "I'd rather be alone then pretend I feel alright!"

author: XCITERO
text: @Tyler Durden I'd say the nostalgia isn't there because this is purely an album of the times we live just now. The Suburbs as an album was able to achieve this nostalgic effect because it was talking about childhood, something we can all relate to. Reflektor is discussing how society at this moment is heavily reliant on technology to function normally; in a few years time (5 years possibly even more), this view of society will become all the more pertinent, and the nostalgia will begin to creep into your listening, if you choose to listen to it in the future.

author: Forrest Gump
text: Can people explain to me what Arcade Fire really offers? A few of my friends are die-hard fans who talk nonstop about them, but I just can't seem to get them. I mean, their music isn't exactly upbeat so you can't feel happy, dance, or just groove along and toe tap, but they're not exactly sad or angry so you can't sit and vibe and sympathize or be pumped. Moreover, musically/composition-wise their music isn't very complicated or interesting (like a solo would be I suppose) and lyrically, well I can't say much since they kind of just mumble and I barely understand half of what they say most of the time..... so what gives?¬†\n\nThis is an actual question - I kind of want to be enlightened so I can at least talk to some of the people I know about them to some degree and not be left out in confusion for an hour or two.

author: thehappiestcamper
text: Everyone talks about Arcade Fire's hype like it's something the band personally does to piss everyone off. Like the band is really that pretentious that THEY'RE the ones writing Pitchfork and NME articles about any time one of them takes a shit. They literally announced their album was coming out THROUGH TWITTER, and it was every major music news site that projected the news. They're one of the simplest bands I know of, at least juxtaposed to their enormous success. They do weird stuff, they wear giant heads on top of their own, and they make people dress up at concerts. But they're not the ones making sure everybody knows about it, they just do what they like and people watch. The people complaining are the ones making all the hype. We get that you're cooler than everybody, and we all hardly suspect your constant reiteration about how shitty Arcade Fire is is just a sad attempt to convince yourself of it. But that being said, it's not like Arcade Fire gives a crap whether you like them or not.

author: Blue in the Muse
text: People's close mindedness always ceases to amaze me, for the fact I was born in the 80's I've been exposed to all kinds of music: pop, rock, grudge, indie, indie rock, post-hardcore, indie pop, indie pop rock, ect. I've been listening to a shit ton of music in the past 29 years of my life, I've always been open minded to new ideas and progressive music genres but lately music has started to become lackluster, I blame American pop culture but who really knows. This is something I've always known, the Canadian music scene has always been full of different, weird and talented artists. And for me I'm pleased with this band seeing as the've worked hard these past 10? Years to get here. Now for those who complain about change in sound take Tegan and Sara for example, the've change their" sound" in every album excluding their 1st and 2nd. What I'm trying to say is try to listen to different genres and take it for what it is; now for me I barely listen to any if not zero American musicians because I find most of that music scene seems to be plagued with the I don't know how to write original songs plague. Also to harken back to what I said about Canada and the unique music scene is that almost 97% of our artists prefer writing their own songs and playing instruments in stead of just preprogrammed shit (not to shit on EDM).

author: talus007
text:
Review of Arcade Fires title track and video: Reflektor
Looking at a computer screen carefully you can see your reflection. As a society we utilize social media to show others a reflection of ourselves.
Arcade Fires title song accompanying video shows that we experience our entire lives through ‚Äúreflections‚Äù. The band does this by singing about reflective technologies in the lyrics, by showing mirror reflectors in the video, reflective symbolism in the video, and music that supports these elements.
The song has a stanza to each of various technologies like Facebook, CDs, computer screens, PRISM surveillance program and the Droste effect to show how instead of enhancing relationships they only show us reflections of ourselves.
The video reinforces these themes with the use of reflective surfaces: a reflective casket to represent the grief we feel that is not for our lost one but for ourselves, a disco ball represents our attempts to define God and Wasserman's knight of the mirrors to remind us that we are ourselves and not who we portray ourselves in social media.
Other symbolism is used in the video that support the main theme. People are depicted in masks that crudely represent themselves. This furthers the theme of the way we are only vaguely represented in our social media interactions. Dolls are used to represent how our experiences are smaller parts of us and how they fall away from us later in life.
Life is depicted in the video as a long dark road that we all travel causing us first to reach for one another, then to look within ourselves, and finally to look for higher purpose.
The song and video, although rife with symbolism, are not always meant to be taken seriously. R√©gine Chassagne sings her lines in French just because she likes singing in French. The mysterious ‚Äúnine‚Äù in the video represents the nine years it took to make the album.
Musically the song is a step up from the band previous works. The band has stated in interviews that Reflekors‚Äô percussion sound was inspired by Haitian carnival music. Rock legend David Bowie assisted with production of the album; His influence can be heard on the title track and he sings on the title track.
Arcade fire lyricist Win Butler has spoken in interviews about his ‚Äúlife changing‚Äù visit to Haiti and Haitian influence on his art. Butler found Haitians had close social ties without the use of modern social media. Drawing on those experiences and the concept of a ‚ÄúReflective Age‚Äù from Kierkegaard‚Äôs work has inspired the ideas for the song; how social media, instead of bringing people closer, just shows them reflections of themselves.

author: Tatiane Miranda
text: I can see many people saying "this is not arcade fire" "this is rubbish" blah blah blah seriously? So I guess you don't know the band at all, or the album. When I listened to this for the first time I got mixed feelings, but it deff grows on you. They don't write songs individually.. Try watching "Black Orpheus" and read about Orpheus and Eurydice history, the whole album is inspired by it. There are still many thinks about the album I'm trying to figure out, but that's just what makes it magnificent. It's not obvious. It makes you think and takes you through an amazing history and a catchy vibe. So instead of criticizing, just try to use your brain harder. If this is not good music, I don't know what is.

text: Arcade Fire is The TRUEST & MOST GENUINE definition of what it means to be band of musicians! For most songs I find I have a preference for the verse over the chorus but not so with this. It's really floated my boat.

author: Paul Roe
text: I really am only aware of what is popular, classic- already known. I don't like trying out things that are new and unfamiliar. My brother is much more with it. He tries to turn me on to new stuff again and again, and also tries to get me to visit Paris to see the latest cool trends and to directly experience the latest cultural movements. But, I am not into it.¬† But, when I finally did listen to my bro and check out the latest in Paris, I was already behind the curve. What I liked was already out of fashion. I have no sense of what is cool, or what is going to be a trend among the cool, and I certainly have no inside knowledge of all those little happenings that those in the know, like hipsters, know about. I am kinda typically the last to know. Know who I am?? I am VINCENT VAN GOGH circa 1887. [All references adopted directly from his letters to his brother Theo, with little or no artistic license] Admit it. You were feeling edgier, superior and more creative than him. Ha!

author: ajdutch79
text: Pretentiousness is partly what the song is about, as shown by the inflated heads in the video. I'm thinking that the desire to relate greater importance than one actually has is one of the themes of the song.¬† Personally, I think its refreshing to see a band write about how we use virtual communication to inflate our own egos. This comment I"m making, for example, may lead me to believe that I'm making a connection with someone, but really I'm just reflecting my own opinion for self- gratification.I probably won't even come back to look at the response. Another example may be what we post on facebook. Often, we are posting more for ourselves than for others. As the song states, "I thought I'd found a connector. Turns out it was just a reflektor." I personally love the message.It's a major topic that very few bands are even considered discussing. I wish more popular music was as intelligent and thoughtful, but that's just my own little reflection.

author: davidheseltine85
text: My 1st impression of this new album was dislike. Then I had a re listen, and I massively changed my mind. Once again Arcade Fire have shown why they were amongst the greatest bands of all time (in my humble opinion). They've created somethig totally different, and unrelated to their previous work, and some of the songs on the album are pure genius. I also rated The Suburbs as their best album yet. I respect your opinion, but all I'll say is give it a few more tries, be a bit more open minded about the music they're trying to create, and if you still think it's shit then fair enough.

author: Coalminds.com
text: @davidheseltine85¬†I've given it a few listens, I still like the same 3 or 4 songs I originally did. With Arcade Fire I've always accepted mediocre musicianship because their sum has always been greater than the parts, but that was when they were playing a style of music they're at least comfortable with. This rhythmn section is just bad at this type of music IMO. ¬†Also my gf is haitian so I'm extremely familiar with the type of sound they're attempting. I listen to it almost daily, and I'm telling you this isn't very good.

text: @Coalminds.com They've added a disco type vibe to a lot of the album which I personally like, I just wasn't expecting it from Arcade Fire. text: well I do really like their new album but I am also wondering what you think are more "hard bop albums". Hey no offence here, just want some good music :P

author: Coalminds.com
text: Hard bop is a style of jazz that to me represents the peak of musicianship, I was just using it as a contrast to this album b/c the playing is so often bad. Sony Rollins Saxophone Colossus is always a good place to start. Any of Booker Little's solo work is great. Coltrane's A Love Supreme or Giant Steps. Mingus Dynasty by Charles Mingus isn't really strictly hard bop throughout but it's great.

author: Raymond L.
text: @Coalminds.com Interesting to find a jazz lover on this post; at the same time, it triggers the question: what is jazz doing here? Being a huge jazz fan myself ( the late '30 to...now), I've always made sure NOT to confuse genres. Jazz musicians worked their life long to¬†become virtuosos, wich¬†is almost¬†mandatory if you want to succeed . About fourty years ago, rock music had its own virtuosos too but, as years and tastes went on, virtuosity leaned the way to a more simplyfied music but still enjoyable. None of AF musicians¬†can be call ¬´ virtuosos¬´ BUT they do compensate with a very rich approach to music, so all this to say : i beleive musical genres should not be compared to eachother. And yes, I am also a huge AF fan, play them all on guitar.....and still crazy about jazz ( but I am not good enough to¬†play some, lol).

author: Oreopagus
text:
In early April 2011, bassist Richard Reed Parry of Arcade Fire began a post ["Hey Canadians!"] at arcadefire (dot) com: "It is about to be voting time. Our current leader has championed some pretty destructive initiatives on everyone's behalf... it‚Äôs really important to get out and vote on May 2nd."

Flash forward to Oct. 26/13, when Parry told CBC arts reporter Pierre Landry: "This album [Reflektor] is about the flip-side or alternate dimension or reverse reality idea. It's not a concept of the album but it is an idea that re-occurs."

In an alternate dimension, perhaps Arcade Fire wrote and recorded "Deflektor" after watching Stephen Harper's Nov. 1/13 speech at the Conservative party's biennial convention in Calgary:

At the convention, in a prism of light
Around us the darkness, darkness of white
We gathered there, and looked on a stage

author: Raymond L.
text: Well Christina, since most of the dudes are too busy insulting everyone, I'll try to explain the whole thing. You see, and contrary to what some say, the lyrics are not enough hence the visual part. The whole album is about Life and Death and what goes on in between. So, as you get older, you change; little by little, you look at things differently each day. By doing so, you leave behind some of the misconception you had to make place to new ones ( dropping the baby dolls along the way). And even if we live in an era of communication, we are more alone than before, spending lots and lots of time in front of our computers. Also, the video deals with the idea that we jumps to conclusions to quickly, blinded by illusions and misunderstandings ( reflections?). Bottom line? We need to wise up and talk rather than just ¬´connect¬ª, stop judging a book by its cover, be less materialistic and more positively open to mankind.\nBut I may be wrong since we are surrounded by so many.....reflections. lol.

author: His Holiness Pope Salty I
text:
Arcade Fire: The most popular band in the world that nobody's ever heard of.

Two straight #1 albums, a Grammy for Album of the Year, multiple appearances on SNL - including one after which NBC actually aired a half-hour documentary on the band (How many bands can lay claim to that?), and yet, I know almost nobody who has a clue who they are, much less know any of their songs.

That pretty much says all you need to know about the state of broadcast radio in America.

Yeah, thanks, Ronald Reagan. Deregulating the broadcast industry was a great idea. Put control of the airwaves in as few hands as possible. Lovely. Because I for one would much rather hear Miley Cyrus another hundred times than, God forbid, Clear Channel or Cumulus actually program in some halfway decent songs to air on any of their their cookie-cutter stations.

author: NotAsian
text: I think those people are literally pushing their music onto the airwaves aka no cost to play it, but good music normally requires royalties when played over the radio and no ones got time for that.\nI don't know why you think lack of regulation is the problem the internet is the least regulated communication technology, its just the limitations of the technology combined with copywrite laws that hold back art.\nDigital radio will allow for more stations so we may see the impacts in a decade or so once everyone is switched.

text: Awards are subjective? Let me explain what subjective is: take, for example, a Champions League final, or any other kind of competition at all. As you know, the best doesn't always win. You may have the best players... you play wonderfully... but if you don't score you don't win. Simple as that. THIS is subjective, not horrible... although sometimes unfair. A Grammy award is NOT a football match. Now we're talking about the National Academy's votes of (mostly) great producers and musicians.

author: Michaela Davis
text: I'm not sure what you just described to me, but certainly is not "subjective". Subjective means that it's relative to the person. What's good to you, obviously is not to me. Awards are subjective whether they're voted on by the academy or regular people like you or I. They are opinion based. There is no machine that calculates the level of talent a band has or the amount of genius in their album. Therefore awards are essentially opinions, not facts, not a sure sign that you're talented. That is why in awards, the best don't always win. And yes I'm aware that the academy is selected for their musical know how, but there are many cases in which people are consulted for their expertise and they end up being wrong.

author: Sedali Boko
text: Meaning of the song: basically they are asking themselves if they will find their loved ones again in heaven. The lyrics say " I thought I found the connector...it's just a reflector", it's just a reflection of heaven, not the real one. So basically they think they are in heaven but their loved ones aren't there and If they loved ones aren't in heaven then "they need something more". ¬†that's what they say through out the song. And at the end they found the door to the real heaven, which is represented by the big globe covered with mirrors. And they are holding naked dolls( new borns) up in air, which means there will finally reborn in that new heaven and They will see their loved ones "on the other side"\n\nAt first I thought the song was creepy, but then aren't we all wondering if there is a life after death? Don't we all want to to see again our friends and family that we lost?

author: 07meganann
text: The "hipsters" as you describe them have long left Arcade Fire. They are one of the biggest bands in the world! They've won Grammys, filled Madison Square Garden, headlined some of the biggest festivals in the world. Most people know who they are if they know anything about music. If anyone tried to act "superior" for knowing Arcade Fire they would be laughed at. None of this takes away that they deserves the notoriety. I hope their music reaches as many people as possible because it‚Äôs good!

author: 07meganann
text: I don't think it has anything to do with being a hipster. I'm not a "hipster" but I love Arcade Fire. Music is so subjective. What speaks to you might not speak to me and vice versa. But to try and answer your orginal question based on my personal preferences, I think what makes Arcade Fire a "big deal" is their uncanny ability to arrange a song, their unusual lyrics, their instrumentation and voices. Finally, I've seen them live and the frenzy they create on stage is astonding.

author: 07meganann
text: Wow. Arcade Fire is truly an incredible band. I think the new album (and this song) capture the frenzy of their life performances. Music is so subjective, and I can understand why people don't like them. However, I think they are the best band of the last decade and they have put out 4 solid albums. They continue to get more interesting, creative, and powerful.

author: Gregorio Ganesh
text: Wow. This is the best band out there now along with Tame Impala. Except this song is way deeper: it's about filling a perceived inner void: "I thought, I found the way to enter" (ultimate joy/enlightenment), "it's just a reflector". "I thought, I found the connector" (An idol that would get me to ultimate joy/enlightenment {fame?}), "it's just a reflector." AF must be meditating deeply on their success as a band, which most  think magically solves all your problems, but ironically only adds more

author: Gregorio Ganesh
text: This song's about things "out there" you think will give you lasting joy, but then once you get them, you soon feel empty inside. So you go after another thing & another, constantly trying to fill up this perceived void. However, it's all "just a reflection": "an outward picture of an inward condition"- (ACIM);  self-perception turned outward. In other words ALL of what we see is inside us - the good, bad & the ugly, but because of our conditioning, we think happiness is "it" & found in objects.

Reflektor is about Mormonism, the faith Win abandoned. "Thought you were praying to the Ressurector (Christ)... thought I found the connector (faith)... thought I found the way to enter (way to enter Heaven)... turns out it was just a reflektor."

Reflector just reflects the light from other objects (or beliefs)... it's not the light. K is denotes satanic/evil.

Dolls in the coffin repressed childhood lost/children sacrificed to this cult.

9 is the # of Judgemnt in the Bible...

Just my opinion

author: Francisco Troy
text: To me, this is a song about the people of my generation (teens/20s) whose lives have become dominated by reflective screens. "When I was 19 and I was staring at a screen" "We're so connected, but are we even friends". These lyrics "reflect" my own experiences with adolescence and the influx of social media (facebook etc) This song acknowledges the superficiality of the digital age we live in. We all looking to connect with people in some way, but maybe what we're really looking for is ourselves.

author: Dillium Kuntz
text: That being said, I don't think the video is deep, profound, or metaphorical in any way.  It  seems like they were having a good time and maybe trying to express the lyrics with attractive imagery.\n\nI don't find the lyrics particularly deep either, though I like them & they do seem to tap into that innate human quality of being just out of reach of some sort of higher understanding.  Like every time we think we're breaking ground, it turns out to be a reflection of what we're really looking for.

author: Dillium Kuntz
text: God & eternity are concepts that exceed the capabilities of human understanding.  The religions of the world appear to be our best attempt at achieving some sort of organized connection to these concepts.  Our attempt at religious/spiritual understanding is akin to kindergartners trying to learn calculus (not that that makes it without merit).\n\nIn short, it appears that the eternal truth is unachievable and that we only see "reflektors", or other humans' fragmented interpretations of the whole.

author: darknightbateman

It kind of leaves me wanting. Like 'a reflection of a reflection of a reflection'. I do admire the symbolism of the 'reflektive' man. How he is a literal mirror of the world he inhabits. Then you hear Bowie - a supreme voice from the vinyl age sing in disappointment: 'Thought you'd bring me to the ressurector - turns out it was just a reflektor'. Aren't we all ditching our reflektors (cds) and going back to vinyl?

author: Samuel Ronca
text: I would actually argue that you are missing the point here. Arcade Fire is an Art Rock band,  and as such their goal isn't just to make music, but to tap into different philosophical movements and ideologies for inspiration. Their goal here was to reference different 80s movements, which is probably where your problem with the originality is rooted. But there is so much more to it. Watch the video again, but ask yourself: "is creation a reflection of its creator , or is it the other way around?"

author: Andrew Dobson
text: My take on this song to date... A commentary on the continuing decay of generative & creative social interaction in lieu of an easy to consume but shallow digital interaction has left us without substance, a reflection of a reflection of a reflection... Our digital alter-ego invades our real life persona until we confuse the two - the outcome in choosing this easy to consume but shallow "One Direction" in life is unfortunately a life without substance or accountability, leading to social decay??

author: Izzy Ell
text: The video is a reflection of the lyrics (pun not intended). My personal interpretation is that everyone's trying to sound smart, everyone's trying to reflect on things, but then everyone ends up reflecting other people's opinions instead of formulating their own theories. Basically, we live in a world full of human beings who think they hold the meaning to life just because they can repeat what others say. They've been playing with the double meaning of reflecting. Hope this helps.

The music has changed, but its still good, and the lyrics are fucking fantastic.

I'll love you forever, Arcade Fire.
